49","Little Thurlow, Suffolk, England":"Little Thurlow, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Wethersfield, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1530–after 1550":"1530–after 1550","1530–1550":"1530–1550","1532–Male":"1532–Deceased","1525–1550":"1525–1550","1550–1620":"1550–1620","1517–1587":"1517–1587","1517–Female":"1517–Deceased","Aft 1550":"after 1550","1550":"1550","Abt 1538":"about 1538","1525":"1525","1544":"1544","1587":"1587","1620":"1620","1532":"1532","1530":"1530","after 1550":"after 1550","about 1550":"about 1550","1517":"1517","1549":"1549","Little Thurlow, Suffolk, England":"Little Thurlow, Suffolk, England","England":"England","Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Wethersfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Livermore","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: probably a habitational name from Livermere in Suffolk. This is first found in the form <i>Leuuremer</i> (<i>c.</i> 1050), which suggests derivation from Old English <i>lǣfer</i> ‘rush, reed’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake’. However, later forms consistently show <i>i</i> in the first syllable, suggesting Old English <i>lifer</i> ‘liver’, referring either to the shape of the pond or to the coagulation of the water."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Samuel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shemuel</i>), possibly meaning ‘He (God) has hearkened’ (presumably to the prayers of a mother for a son). It may also be understood as a contracted form of Hebrew <i>sha'ulme'el</i> meaning ‘asked of God’. In the case of Samuel the son of Hannah, this would be more in keeping with his mother's statement ‘Because I have asked him of the Lord’ (1 Samuel 1:20). Living in the 11th century  bc , Samuel was a Hebrew judge and prophet of the greatest historical importance, who established the Hebrew monarchy, anointing as king both Saul and, later, David. In the Authorized Version two books of the Old Testament are named after him, although in Roman Catholic and Orthodox versions of the Bible they are known as the first and second Book of Kings. The story of Samuel being called by God while still a child serving in the house of Eli the priest (1 Samuel 3) is of great vividness and has moved countless generations. In England and America the name was particularly popular among the 16th-century Puritans and among Nonconformists from the 17th to the 19th century. It became fashionable again in the 1990s."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Samuel Livermore was born in 1530, in Little Thurlow, Suffolk, England, his father, William Livermore, was 13 and his mother, Mrs. Rebecca Livermore, was 14. He married Anna Bridge in 1544, in Little Thurlow, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1550, in his hometown."},"et":{"1530–after 1550":"1530–pärast 1550","1530–1550":"1530–1550","1532–Male":"1532–Surnud","1525–1550":"1525–1550","1550–1620":"1550–1620","1517–1587":"1517–1587","1517–Female":"1517–Surnud","Aft 1550":"pärast 1550","1550":"1550","Abt 1538":"umbes 1538","1525":"1525","1544":"1544","1587":"1587","1620":"1620","1532":"1532","1530":"1530","after 1550":"pärast 1550","about 15